[{"id":"VR856262","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR856258.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Is the image formed by the mirror real or virtual when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>? What evidence or reasoning helps support the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR856262_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<html><body><div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram consisting of, from left to right along a horizontal line, a convex mirror, an object pointing upward at point P, and point Q. A note states that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR856258.g01.svg\"/></div><p class=\"passage_para\">An object is placed in front of a convex mirror, as shown in the figure. The object is initially located at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>. A second point, Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>, is twice as far from the mirror as Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>.</p></div></div></div></body></html>"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Real. The image is inverted relative to the objectâ€™s original orientation.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Real. The rays from the object and the rays forming the image are all on the same side of the mirror.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Virtual. There is only one focal point for the mirror.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Virtual. Light rays from a point on the object diverge after reflection.</p>"],"answer":3}]